{"id":"1401.5901","submitter":"Ralf Metzler","authors":"Henning Kruesemann, Aljaz Godec, and Ralf Metzler","title":"First passage statistics for aging diffusion in annealed and quenched\n  disorder","comments":"5 pages, 4 Figures, RevTeX","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 89, 040101(R) (2014)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.89.040101","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech q-bio.QM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Aging, the dependence of the dynamics of a physical process on the time $t_a$\nsince its original preparation, is observed in systems ranging from the motion\nof charge carriers in amorphous semiconductors over the blinking dynamics of\nquantum dots to the tracer dispersion in living biological cells. Here we study\nthe effects of aging on one of the most fundamental properties of a stochastic\nprocess, the first passage dynamics. We find that for an aging continuous time\nrandom walk process the scaling exponent of the density of first passage times\nchanges twice as the aging progresses and reveals an intermediate scaling\nregime. The first passage dynamics depends on $t_a$ differently for\nintermediate and strong aging. Similar crossovers are obtained for the first\npassage dynamics for a confined and driven particle. Comparison to the motion\nof an aged particle in the quenched trap model with a bias shows excellent\nagreement with our analytical findings. Our results demonstrate how first\npassage measurements can be used to unravel the age $t_a$ of a physical system.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 23 Jan 2014 09:21:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-12-24"}
